few of the windows held no lights - the tower looked dark on the inside. Considering the time of day, it wasn't for the night. Was the place empty? She continued to examine it at a distance for a little longer, debating.The cloak parted and lifted into the pair of mighty wings, and with a leap she was airborne. She flew up against the droplets that descended, and brought herself to that balcony - quick rotation of her wings easing her descent as her boots found the stones. With a turn she looked down to the earth far below, and her heart skipped a beat. She enjoyed being high up, and this was fantastic. Her smile widened, and she turned to look upon the tower that was perched at one end of the platform. Moving around it she saw the door leading inside, and eased her hand out to find the heavy metal ring of a knob.It opened... with no resistance. It wasn't locked. She would push the door open to find the landing room very plain, near empty. There wasn't a single light within, and very little in terms of furniture. She would slip inside and shut the door behind her - slipping the bolt latch to the side and effectively locking it in her wake. She would bring a hand up and gather her energy into a tight concentration in her palm, soon casting back the darkness with a brilliant ball of fire that manifested in her hand. She found stairs of a wood cut ascending higher, and thick cut stone steps leading below. She took the ones below, and as she left the floor above she saw down into the greeting area below - occasionally broken along the stairs with a few more doors. Storage, and a couple of guest rooms. But still relatively barren, and dusty from lack of occupants. Further down, beneath an old carpet, there was a hidden door to the cellar - which was ominous in feel from the lack of anything down there and no light. The entire place was just so... empty.She shut the cellar door and brought her eyes to the front door. The latch wasn't set - it was unlocked. This place was truly abandoned. Her steps brought her near, and a hand extended to grasp at the bolt latch. She took a breath, and pushed it into place to lock the door - the sound of that metal hitting in place echoing up the empty tower. It felt like a revelation of sorts - she had come in and locked the place down. Did... this make it her tower now? It certainly felt like it. If the place had been clean she would have assumed there were people that lived here... but it was quite the opposite.Zera turned in place and tilted her head, looking up the vacant tower once more. This place had much potential to be a dwelling. Her mind started to piece together how she could shape it... what she might build into the foundation. This entryway could make for a cozy entrance, perhaps a small kitchen. Closest storage for food. The landing above - a study. Maybe even... cut out the wall to the platform for an archway - a proper balcony.She had to laugh and shake her head, clear her thoughts. She was becoming giddy with all the possibilities. In her absolute delight her wings came out and flapped hard to carry her the distance to the top of the spiraling stairs, where she rushed the landing room and the door - unlocking it quickly. Outside, she darted across the platform and let her wings stretch out high and as far as they could go. She ignored the rain that had started to fall, far too elated to care. With a ring of laughter she began to spin and sway into dance. It was an odd sensation she couldn't quite control - a place to build into her own made her absolutely ecstatic. It was a sense of purpose, if only for now. She would follow through on it.", "link_list": [], "image_list": [], "html": "<font face=\"georgia\">Her steps carried her along, winding through the streets and along the way within the massive city. It was certainly odd to be within stone and mortar dwellings again, but not as unnerving as she thought it might be. She kept moving, paying little heed to the occasional drop of 